WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.920
All of rstudio's professional products support proxied authentication.

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:07.680
Today we'll look at an example specifically for Shiny Server Pro,

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:13.040
but the process is similar for both rstudio Connect and rstudio Server Pro as well.

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:15.280
Before looking at proxied authentication,

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.320
it's important to understand the regular authentication workflow.

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:23.120
The first step is that a user will request a piece of content.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:27.920
If that content is restricted or requires authentication,

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:32.240
Shiny Server Pro will respond to the client asking for the user's credentials,

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:34.000
typically a username and password.

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:36.639
Once the credentials are received,

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:43.279
Shiny Server Pro will check to make sure that the credentials are in fact correct,

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:47.520
and it'll do so by looking against either a flat file database

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:53.759
or one of the authentication services specified in the Shiny Server Pro configuration file,

00:00:53.759 --> 00:00:59.279
for example, the authldap directive or the authad directive.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:06.879
If the username and password supplied by the user matches up with those on file,

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:11.519
Shiny Server Pro will then proceed to check whether or not the user has access

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:16.800
to a specific piece of content specified in the Shiny Server Pro configuration file

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:20.160
as the required user or required group directive.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:25.760
If indeed the user has access, Shiny Server Pro will serve the content

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:29.519
and note that the username is available to the application developer

00:01:29.519 --> 00:01:32.400
in the session$user object.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:35.120
Again, there are two primary steps.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:38.639
The first is the user proving that they are who they say they are,

00:01:39.279 --> 00:01:43.680
and the second is determining which content the user has access to

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.120
and then serving that content.

00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:47.599
In proxied authentication,

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:52.720
we have the same workflow, but steps two and step three are outsourced to a proxy server.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:57.919
Specifically, a user will request a piece of Shiny content,

00:01:57.919 --> 00:02:00.800
and that request will be routed through the proxy server.

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.320
The proxy server will then communicate with the user to ID who they are

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:08.479
and to confirm that they are who they say they are,

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:11.839
and this process, if they're already logged in,

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:16.160
can be done via single sign-on without direct involvement from the user.

00:02:17.039 --> 00:02:20.399
Once the proxy server has authenticated the user,

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:23.759
it'll pass the user information to Shiny Server Pro

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:28.320
through a secure HTTP header that contains a key-value pair.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:32.559
The key can be specified inside of the Shiny Server Pro configuration file.

00:02:33.279 --> 00:02:36.399
Shiny Server Pro will then accept that the user is

00:02:36.399 --> 00:02:39.119
who the proxy server has identified them to be.

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:44.000
A note of caution, be sure Shiny Server will only accept

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
incoming requests from the proxy,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.679
because Shiny Server Pro accepts these requests as truth.

00:02:49.679 --> 00:02:53.119
If a user were to sign their own HTTP header,

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:55.279
Shiny Server Pro would trust them as well.

00:02:55.279 --> 00:02:59.279
So all requests should go to Shiny Server Pro through the proxy.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:05.039
Then Shiny Server Pro, after receiving the authenticated username,

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:08.559
proceeds as before by checking whether the user has access

00:03:08.559 --> 00:03:12.160
to a specific piece of content, and if they do, serving that content.

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:19.119
Typically, the proxy server can come in a variety of different forms.

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:25.679
Today, we'll look at a specific example using a tool called OAuth 2 Proxy,

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:30.160
which is an open-source piece of software that allows the user

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:33.199
to communicate with a variety of OAuth 2 providers,

00:03:33.199 --> 00:03:35.119
specifically, in this case, GitHub.

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:38.399
If you are interested in the details,

00:03:38.399 --> 00:03:43.839
please take a look at the Bitly GitHub page for OAuth 2 Proxy.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.240
It describes the steps necessary to set up this particular proxy server,

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:50.720
as well as the OAuth 2 endpoints.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:55.440
And specifically, today, we'll be using GitHub as our OAuth 2 provider.

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:01.119
Inside of GitHub, under Settings, you can specify an OAuth application,

00:04:01.119 --> 00:04:02.320
which is what we've done here.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:09.360
So I'm going to go and request a piece of content from Shiny Server.

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:16.320
Right now, I'm running Shiny Server Pro, and the proxy, both on localhost.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:18.880
The proxy is listening on port 80.

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:22.640
Shiny Server Pro is listening on port 3838.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:27.359
So I'm going to go through the proxy by requesting the Shiny Server Pro content

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:29.519
just at port 80 or localhost.

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:33.519
You'll see that the proxy, OAuth 2 Proxy,

00:04:33.519 --> 00:04:35.839
is asking me to sign in with my GitHub account.

00:04:36.399 --> 00:04:37.839
So I'll proceed to do so.

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:51.519
And after signing in, the GitHub has authenticated me,

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:55.519
passed that authentication back to the OAuth 2 proxy server,

00:04:55.519 --> 00:04:58.799
which has then forwarded my username to Shiny Server Pro.

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:03.760
You can see that Shiny Server Pro is now aware of who I am, logged in as Sean.

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:07.760
If I were to do this again, so to open up a new window,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.880
and to, again, request Shiny Server Pro via the proxy server,

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:18.480
you'll see that this time I am directed directly to Shiny Server

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:22.160
because the browser has cached the authentication cookie.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:27.200
So it knows who I am, and therefore, single sign-on is achieved

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:31.119
because I don't have to directly involve myself in the authentication process.

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:35.839
We still walk through the proxy server, communicating with the GitHub client,

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:39.760
and then passing along the HTTP header to Shiny Server Pro.

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:42.720
But all of that is done on my behalf by the browser.

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:47.760
Hopefully, this gives you a good starting point for setting up

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:51.679
your own proxied server and successfully authenticating users.

00:05:51.679 --> 00:05:52.640
Thank you.

